<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-733-568  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 733 568.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Byte  August 1990 v15 n8 p211(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Full circle. (application-related languages make the usersprogrammers again)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Cook, Rick.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Application-related programming facilities, often known asscripting or macro capabilities, bring programming back to the enduser.andP;  Development of more sophisticated, flexible and powerfulapplications has been accompanied by methods for applying thesoftware to particular user requirements and work.andP;  Examplesinclude AutoCAD's AutoLisp, Hypertalk and user programminglanguages that accompany dBASE and other data base managementsystems.andP;  These languages are either designed to be 'friendly'(HyperTalk) for the general computer user or provide power andflexibility (AutoLisp) for the power user, often at the sacrificeof ease-of-use.andP;  BASIC, Pascal and C tend to be popular models forimplementing user languages, but iconic, object-oriented languagesare growing in use.andP;  The lack of standardization of userlanguages, communications between languages and future directionsare discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Applications ProgrammingEnd UsersProgram Development ToolsTrendsImpact AnalysisProducts.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>